message.content: Pinus flexilis, commonly known as the limber pine, is a species of coniferous tree belonging to the Pinaceae family. It can grow up to 20-40 meters tall and has a rounded crown with a straight trunk. The bark is thick, scaly, and grayish-brown in color. The needles of the tree are flexible, slender, and vary from blue-green to dark green in color. The cones are large, cylindrical, and have a curved or slightly twisted shape. The wood of Pinus flexilis is durable, hard, and has a yellowish-white color. The tree is commonly found in mountainous regions of western North America, ranging from Canada to Mexico, and is used for timber, hiking trails, and as a landscaping ornamental plant. Overall, Pinus flexilis is characterized by its tall stature, scaly bark, flexible needles, and twisted cones.
